The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   BCCI bar on Laxman, Chawla  New Delhi: The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) has advised leg-spinner Piyush Chawla and batsman VVS Laxman not to play for English counties that have players from rebel Indian Cricket League. BCCI secretary Niranjan Shah said both Chawla and Laxman have been asked to avoid playing for Hampshire and Nottinghamshire respectively. Both Hampshire and Nottinghamshire have three players who have aligned with the ICL in their sides.  Bats stolen  Sydney: Four valuable cricket bats signed by Australian batting legend Sir Donald Bradman have been stolen from a sports shop, police said on Thursday. The bats, together valued at $39,050, were taken from a shop in the northern city of Darwin. Thieves smashed in a front window, police said.  Icon status  Durban: Future Test series between South Africa and England have been granted lsquo;icon rsquo; status, placing them in the same bracket along with the traditional Ashes series between England and Australia. CSA said in a release that the proposal has been agreed to in principle by the ECB.  Wright choice  Christchurch: Former India coach John Wright has been touted as the first choice to replace John Bracewell as New Zealand coach after the New Zealand Cricket Board (NZC) openly invited the former batsman to take up the reins of the senior side. NZC chief executive Justin Vaughan said if Wright was ready to return to the international arena, he was most welcome.   ICC briefing  New Delhi: The ICC will brief representatives of the eight Champions Trophy teams on Sunday about security for the September one-day tournament in Pakistan.   Prakash wins  New Delhi: Indian Davis Cupper Prakash Amritraj pulled off an upset win over top seed Amer Delic to advance into the singles second round of the $75,000 ATP Challenger tournament in Aptos. According to information received here, Amritraj toppled his American opponent 6-4, 4-6, 6-3.  Sania loses  New Delhi: Sania and her Russian partner Anna Chakvetadze were brushed aside by unheralded Czech pair of Eva Hrdinova and Vladimira Uhlirova 6-3, 6-4 in the WTA Bank of the West Classic at Stanford.  Indians out  Indianapolis: Top seeds Leander Paes and Mahesh Bhupathi crashed out of the Indianapolis tennis championship with a first round defeat. The lsquo;Indian Express rsquo; pair lost to the Canadian duo of Daniel Nestor and Frederic Niemeyer 4-6, 6-3, 10-12 in a one hour and 25 minutes.
                                                                                                                                                               
